No, enabling -std=c++2c in GCC does not provide std::execution by default.
While GCC supports experimental C++26 features via -std=c++2c, std::execution (based on P2300) is not part of the compiler’s built-in library (libstdc++), even with this flag.

You must manually include and link the NVIDIA stdexec library to use the Sender/Receiver model.
2. Will the standardized std::execution be based on NVIDIA’s stdexec?

Yes.
The std::execution framework in C++26 is directly based on NVIDIA’s stdexec implementation of P2300.

    It has been accepted into C++26.

    stdexec is the reference implementation and is being used for real-world testing and feedback.

    The final std::execution will be functionally equivalent, though minor naming or structural changes may occur before standardization. 

3. What is CPM, and do you need it if you're using -std=c++2c?

CPM (CMake Package Manager) is a lightweight, header-only script that simplifies dependency management in CMake projects. It wraps CMake’s FetchContent module to provide:

    Easy integration of Git-based or URL-based dependencies

    Version control

    Caching

    Simple syntax (e.g., CPMAddPackage("gh:NVIDIA/stdexec")) 

You need CPM (or an equivalent) because:

    -std=c++2c only enables language features, not library components.

    std::execution is a library framework, not built into GCC/libstdc++ yet.

    You must externally include stdexec to use the concurrency model.

Using CPM is the recommended way to integrate stdexec into your CMake project.
