To establish trust in public keys for metadata signing, use one of these models:
1. Web of Trust (WoT)

    Users personally verify key fingerprints (e.g., via video call or in-person).

    They sign the public key to vouch for its authenticity.

    Others can trust keys indirectly if signed by trusted parties (e.g., GnuPG model). 

2. Explicit Key Trust Model

    Trust is based on secure out-of-band distribution of public keys.

    The backend hardcodes or securely fetches trusted keys (e.g., via a known URL or embedded list).

    Used by federations like InCommon for SAML metadata.

3. PKI / Certificate Authority (CA) Model

    Public keys are bundled in X.509 certificates issued by a trusted CA.

    The backend validates the certificate chain up to a trusted root.

    Requires maintaining a trust store of root CA certificates.

Recommendation

