A Zero-Knowledge Proof (ZKP) is a cryptographic method where one party (the prover) can prove to another (the verifier) that a statement is true without revealing any additional information.
How It Helps in Your System

    Privacy: A creator can prove they own a private key or signed metadata without revealing the key or full data.

    Selective Disclosure: Prove specific facts (e.g., “I am an authorized creator”) without exposing identity.

    Security: No sensitive data (like private keys) is transmitted or stored on the backend.

    Trust Minimization: Reduces reliance on third parties — trust comes from math, not intermediaries.

Example Use Case

A creator submits metadata with a ZKP showing:

    “I signed this using the private key matching public key X.”

    The backend verifies the proof without ever seeing the private key. 

This enhances security and privacy while maintaining verifiability.
